Econometrics Final Exam Review 2017 F
This is an review sheet for SMU's Econometrics Final 2017F. The list of topics include:

chapter-3.html.title: Chapter 3
chapter-3.html.body:
Chapter 3 : Concepts and Theorems
Gauss-Markov Assumptions (MLR.1 - MLR.5)

MLR.1 (Linear in Parameters)


The relationship between y and x is linear. partial derivative of any given independent variable must be constant.
y = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1} x + u

MLR.2 (Random Sampling)


{(x_{i},y_{i}): i= 1,...,n}
Guarantees that values of independent variable are not correlated.
In Time Series, the assumption is omitted.

MLR.3 (No Perfect Collinearity)


None of the independent variables should be a multiple of another
None has perfect correlation with a linear combination of the others
This would mean that some variable was redundant - can’t ”identify” the parameters
Note that you can have some colinearity, just not Perfect Correlation. For instant, we can and have ran regression using educ2 = educ^2 along with educ. However we will not be able to run a regression using educ10 = 10 * educ along with educ.

MLR.4 (Zero Conditional Mean)


the zero conditional mean assumption is much more likely to hold because fewer things end up in the error. In which case no significant causal variables is omitted, guaranteeing no correlation between error terms and the independent variables.

MLR.5 (Homoskedasticity)


Var (u_{i} | x_{i})=\sigma^2
variability of the unobserved influences does not depend on the value of the explanatory (x) variable. This saves us from the risk of overestimating the correlations.
What is Gauss-Markov Theorem?

Gauss-Markov Theorem 3.4


Under MLR.1-MLR.5, the OLS estimator is the Best Linear Unbiased Estimator(BLUE) of the regression coefficients
Var (\hat{\beta_{j}}) \leq Var (\tilde{\beta_{j}})    ,    j = 0, 1, ... , k
for all   \displaystyle \sum_{i=1}^n w_{ij}y_{i}   for which   E(\tilde{\beta_{j}}) = \beta_{j}  ,  j = 0, 1, ... , k
What does BLUE mean?
Best Linear Unbiased Estimator.
OLS Estimates

Random Sample -> as we've seen from the assumptions
Regression Residuals (\hat{u}_{i} = y_{i} - \hat{\beta_{0}} - \hat{\beta_{1}}(x_{i1}) \ ... \  \hat{\beta_{k}}(x_{ik})) -> this means residuals are the unexplained difference between our input and output.
Minimized Sum of Squared Residuals (min \displaystyle \sum_{i=1}^n \hat{u_{i}^2} \  \rightarrow \ \hat{\beta_{0}}, \hat{\beta_{1}}, ... , \hat{\beta_{k}} ) -> since we have minimized variance between observed data and prediction this is good. In most cases computation will do the minimization.
Coefficient Interpretation (\beta_{j} = \Delta{y} \over \Delta{x_{j}}) -> Ceteris Paribus, how much does y change by 1 unit change in jth independent variable.

Interpretation of Coefficients / Slope Estimates

Regular

y = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1}x + u
per UNIT increase in x cause \beta_{1} UNIT increase in y
I.E : collegeGPA \ = \ 1.29 + 0.453 \ highschoolGPA
So collegeGPA is increased by 0.453 unit if highschoolGPA is increased by 1 unit

Logarithmic Dependent Variable


\log{(y)} = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1}x + u
per UNIT increase in x cause \beta_{1} PERCENT increase in y
I.E : \log{(wage)} \ = \ 4.175 + 0.142 \ experience
So wage is increased by 14.2% per UNIT increase in experience.

Logarithmic Dependent and Independent Variable


\log{(y)} = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1}\log{(x)} + u
per PERCENT increase in x cause \beta_{1} PERCENT increase in y
I.E : \log{wage} \ = \ 4.175 + 0.42 \log{(age)}
So wage is increased by 0.42% per UNIT increase in experience. You do not have to multiply the coefficient by 100 because log of age is already doing that for you in the regression.
 
Goodness of Fit (R^2)
Can only increase if another explanatory variable is added to the regression.
R^2 = (\displaystyle \sum_{i=1}^n (y_{i} - \tilde{y})(\tilde{y_{i}} - \tilde{\hat{y}}))^2 \over (\displaystyle \sum_{i=1}^n (y_{i} - \tilde{y})^2)(\displaystyle \sum_{i=1}^n (\hat{y_{i}} - \tilde{\hat{y}})^2)
Let's look at what the hell this means :)SST(Total Sum of Squares) = SSR(Sum of Squared Regression) + SSE (Sum of Squared Erros)
SSR : Sum of squared differences between the prediction for each observation, and the population mean(y).
SSE : Sum of deviation of the response values from the fit to the response values
R^2 \equiv { SSE \over SST} = {1- {SSR \over SST}}
So R^2 is the ratio of difference in observed and  predicted value in regards to the total difference.
If another explanatory variable is added to the regression SSR would decrease, thus increasing R^2. In fact, that is the only way for goodness of fit to increase.
Multicolinearity
Two explanatory variables are closely related. This usually means that they are multiples of each other, and thus one must be eliminated in order for regression to work.
Variance of OLS Estimators
As touched in MLR.5, homoskedasticity assumes that value of independent variable must not contain any information regarding variance of unobserved factors.
Var ( { \hat { \beta_{ j } } } ) = { { \sigma^2 } \over { SST_{ j } ( 1-R^2_{ j } ) } }
j = 1, 2, ... , k
\sigma^2 is the variance of error term. SST_{j} is the total sample variation in variable x_{j}. R^2_{j} is the goodness of fit from a regression of variable x_{j} on all other independent variables including the constant.

Error Variance

High error variance will increase the sampling variance due to higher "noise" in the equation. Greater the error variance, less reliable the precision of the estimates. Error variance will not decrease even if you decrease the sample size.

Total Sample Variation in independent variable

More sample variation leads to more precise estimates. Total sample variation increases with the sample size. Therefore Increasing thesample size is a way to get more precise estimates. All this means is that more data you have, more precise your estimates will be.
Error Variance
Homoskedasticity vs Heteroskedasticity : Whether the error variance has any relationship to the explanatory variable. Good way to abstract the relationship would be to take the log of variables in regression.
Omitting and Including a Variable (Type 1 vs Type 2 Error)
If you are including irrelevant variable (Type II error), the regression will not be affected. However this will increase your standard error.
If you omit a relevant variable (Type I error), the regression will not give you a meaningful outcome.
We have Hypothesis Testing for this.

chapter-4.html.title: Chapter 4
chapter-4.html.body:
Chapter 4 : Multiple Linear Regression
Multiple Linear Regression

MLR.6 : Normality of the Error Term

This assumes unobserved factors and their variance are normally distributed around the population regression function regardless of explanatory variable.
u_{i} \tilde{} Normal(0,\sigma^2), Independent from x_{i1}, x_{i2}, ... , x_{ik}
y|x \tilde{} Normal(\beta_{0} + \beta_{1}x_{1} + ... + \beta_{k}x_{k} , \sigma^2 )
The error term is the sum of many different unobserved factors.
Sum of independent factors are normaly distributed by Central Limit Theorem.

Normality and its problems

Problems:

How many is "many" factors? What number do we need to have? -> Sample Size \geq 31, Degree of Freedom \geq120
Possibly very heterogenuous distribution of individual factors -> Assumption is wrong for certain samples.
How independent are the different factors? -> Colinearity Problem

Really the biggest problem with normality assumption of error terms is that it is empirical. In many cases normality is impossible or questionable by definition. However Inductively we can conclude that at the very least the error distribution will be "close" to normal distribution.
Normality does not hold for values that cannot be negative like wage or time, and values that will inevitably have limitted integer outcomes such as number of arrests (most people would have arrests ranging from 0 ~ 10.), or dummy variables such as female, or unemployeed (binary value.)
As mentioned in Chapter 3, the best way to normalize the data is by log transformation. First try taking log of dependent variable.
Normality is the most important assumption in using OLS because this trait determines the BUE (doesn't even have to be linear!) of estimator.
For Statistical Inference, normality can be substituted by large sample size.
While MLR.1 - MLR.5 is referred to as the Gauss-Markov Assumption, including normality, MLR.1 - MLR.6 is referred to as  "Classical Linear Model(CLM) assumptions"

Theorem 4.1 : Normal Sampling Distribution

With CLM, we know
\hat{\beta_{j}} \tilde{} {Normal({\beta_{j}},{Var(\hat{\beta_{j}})})}, where the \hat{\beta_{j}}  represents estimators normally distributed around the actual parameter with the variance.
{ { \hat { \beta_{ j } }- \beta_{ j } } \over { std ( \hat {  \beta_{ j } } ) } }  ~  Normal(0, 1) where the standarized estimators will follow a standard Normal distribution ranging from 0 ~ 1.
Hypothesis Testing
T-Test 
T-tests are used to test the significance of an explanatory variable.
Let's assume the following Regression Eqaution.
log{(y)} = \underset{(0.05)}{0.1} + \underset{(0.2)}{0.5}x_{1} + ... + \underset{(stddev_{j})}{\beta_{j}}x_{j}
where
Intercept : \beta_{0} = 0.1 , \sigma_{0} = 0.05,
Coefficient1 : \beta_{1} = 0.5,  \sigma_{1} = 0.2
Coefficientj : \beta_{j} = \beta_{j} , \sigma_{j} = stddev_{j}
Sample size :  n = 500
Goodness of fit : R^2 = 0.315

Set up the Null and Alternative Hypothesis and Alternative Hypothesis
Null Hypothesis : Assumes that effect of independent variable \beta_{j}{x_{j}} is equal to Zero, thus the variable is statistically insignificant.
Alternative Hypothesis : Assumes that effect of independent variable \beta_{j}{x_{j}} is greater or less than Zero, thus the variable is statistically significant. (Let's use greater than > for now. It can be substituted with \neq, or )
Notation would be, Test H_{0} : \beta_{j}{x_{j}} = 0 against Ha : \beta_{j}{x_{j}} \gt 0
Let's assume for the example, that we are testing for significance of x_{1}. So our hypothesis would be :
Test H_{0} : \beta{x_{1}} = 0 against Ha : \beta{x_{1}} \gt 0


Get the T-statistics
t-statistic is the coefficient of independent variable divided by its standard deviation.
t_{\hat{\beta_{j}}} \equiv {\hat{\beta_{j}} \over {se(\hat{\beta_{j}})}}
T-statistic is used to test the null hypothesis. Farther the estimated Coefficient is away from zero, more likely it is that we will reject null hypothesis. So in hypothesis test we see if the estimated coefficient is "far enough" from zero.
How far is the "far enough"? That will depend on the variability of the coefficient, like the standard deviation. It is the unit by which we measure this "farness." T-statistic measures how many estimated standard deviations away the estimated coefficient is away from zero. 
In a generic form, we will have t_{x_{j}} = { {\beta_{j}} \over {\sigma_{j}} } .  For our example :
t_{x_{1}} = { {0.5} \over {0.2} } \approx 2.5


Calculate Degree of Freedom

Degree of Freedom is used in looking up the critical value. It represents the number of values in the final calculation that are free to vary.

You calculate this by  n - k - 1, where n = sample size and k = number of independent variables. In our case, we have j independent variables. Let's say j = 3. In which case, we have df = 500 - 3 - 1 = 496



Get the critical value

Critical Value is a threshold that you use to accept or reject null hypothesis. It is different for varying degree of freedom and significance level. Notation for Critival Value is c_{\alpha}, where alpha is a value between 0 and 1 (ideally at most 0.2). Below is a table for looking up critical values.

Confidence Interval is the Center Area of the distribution. CI of 95% means that the 2.5% of the distribution is cut out on each end. Since we cut out parts from both ends, or tails of the distribution, we call this a two tail test. The Center Area is 1 - \alpha, where alpha stands for tail areas. For 95% CI, \alpha = 0.05) Note that this is a Two Tail test. For one tail test, alpha value will be half of two tail test's.

At 95% confidence interval and df \gt 120, it's good to remember that c_{0.05} = 1.96.

With our example, we will assume we want to test the hypothesis on 95% confidence interval. Since CI = 1 - \alpha in a two tail test, we know that \alpha_{j} = 1- 0.95 = 0.05. We already know that our df > 120. So look at the table to see the df > 120, and alpha value at 0.05. You can see that the critical value or c_{0.05} = 1.960. Or, you can conviniently remember this number.

Now, Compare the critival value to the t-statistic.

If critical value x_{j} on dependent variable y is statistically greater than zero at c \% significance level, thus statistically significant at c \% level."

If critical value > t-statistic, accept null hypothesis and conclude that "The effect of independent variable x_{j} on dependent variable y is statistically equal to zero at c \% significance level, thus statistically insignificant at c \% level.

For our example, we have t_{x_{1}} \approx 2.5 and c_{0.05} = 1.960. We can see that 2.5 > 1.960, so the t-statistic is greater than the c-value.

Thus we will conclude : "The effect of independent variable x_{1} on dependent variable y is statistically greater than zero at 5% significance level and thus statistically significant at 5% level."

On the other hand, if we use different threshold, for instance 99% Confidence Interval, we will get c_{0.01} = 2.576. We can see that 2.5 , thus we will conclude "The effect of independent variable x_{1} on dependent variable y is statistically equal to zero at 1% significance level and thus statistically insignificant at 1% level."




F-Test
F-test tests exclusion restictions.
With this test, we are trying to see if the variances of two different sets are the same. This is useful because you can use F-test to see whether a variable is significant given the other variables in the regression.
F-test joins the multiple tests for significance testing. Conceptually, given equation :
log{(y)} = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1}x_{1} + \beta_{2}x_{2} + \beta_{3}x_{3}
We will have null and alternative hypothesis :
Test H_{0} : \beta_{1} = 0, \beta_{2} = 0, \beta_{3} = 0 against H_{a} : H_{0} \  is \  false
At a glance, the F-test has much harsher standard for accepting the null hypothesis given that all of these conditions must be met. However we use F-test for variables that will normally (With T-Test) be considered insignificant. Let's make a real number example.

Unrestricted Model (Do not drop insignificant variables)

log{(y)} = \underset{(11.19)}{0.29} + \underset{(0.0713)}{0.0125}x_{1} +
\underset{(0.0202)}{0.0013}x_{2} + \underset{(0.00110)}{0.00098}x_{3} + \underset{(0.0144)}{0.0161}x_{4} + \underset{(0.0108)}{0.0072}x_{5}
n = 353, \  SSR = 183.186, \  R^2 = 0.6278
Without even doing the full t-test, you can see that all independent variables past x2 will be insignificant at 95% confidence interval because the standard deviation is bigger than the coefficient, or only slighly smaller. We know that this will force t-statistic to be smaller than 1.00 for most of these, and we already saw that even with alpha value as large as 0.2 the critical value is 1.282, which is still greater than 1.00.
So for above model, we will run a F-test.
Note that we have SSR this time. If the insignificant variables are dropped, the SSR will increase and goodness of fit will decrease by definition. What we want to know is whether this increase in SSR is significant. In other words, does dropping seemingly insignificant variables (that we found using t-test) change anything in regression?

Restricted Model (Drop the insignificant variables)

log{(y)} = \underset{(11.19)}{0.29} + \underset{(0.0713)}{0.0125}x_{1} +
\underset{(0.0202)}{0.0013}x_{2}
n = 353, \  SSR = 198.311, \  R^2 = 0.5971
With both Models, lets compute the F-statistic.
{ F = { { ( SSR{ r } - SSR{ ur } ) / q } \over { SSR_{ ur } / ( n-k-1 ) } } } 
F   ~   { F_{ q , \ n-k-1 } }
where
SSR_{r} : SSR of restricted model. The increase in SSR when null hypothesis is accpted follows F-distribution.
SSR_{ur} : SSR of unrestricted model
q : Number of Restrictions (How many variables did you drop?)
(n-k-1) : degree of freedom (note that k is total number of independent variables or independent varaibles of unrestricted model)
CI = 0.99
\alpha = 0.01
Note that Confidence interval is set at very high level in order to be absolutly sure when we are dropping the restroction or the insignificant independent variable. Now let's do F-Test

Compute F-statistic
{ F = { { ( 198.311 - 183.186 ) / 3 } \over { 183.186 / ( 353-5-1 ) } } } \approx 9.55


Get Critical Value
F  ~  F_{3, \ 347} \rightarrow c_{0.01} = 3.782
The critical value can be looked up from F-distribution Table. Let's assume I know what I'm doing and not actually generate multiple tables using multiple alpha value. Because we have q, df, and alpha value to consider, the table for F-distribution either has to be 3 dimensional, drawn in Karnaugh Maps or be separated into multiple tables.
Just to leave no stone unturned, here's how you look up the critical value from F-distribution table.
First find your alpha/p value. (ie. p = 0.01) 0.01 is pretty standard.
In that table, look at the top row and find the column with your q value. (ie. 3)
Down that row, look at the left most column and find your df (ie. 343)
That's the value you need to use.
Check the above work with F-distribution Table from UCLA resource.


Now, check the probability of your F-distribution critical value being greater than your computed F-statistic.
That is, P(F-distribution \  > \ F-statistic ) = m \ | \ 0.000 \leq m \leq 1.000
the probabilty m must be between 0 and 1.
For our example, P(3.782 \  > \ 9.55 ) = 0.000. Obviously because their's no fking way that 9.55 is less than 3.782.




Draw conclusion  

If F-distribution > F-statistic, then you cannot reject the null hypothesis. The variables you had were useless. You say "these variables are jointly insignificant."  
If F-distribution 
For our case, the null hypothesis is rejected hard. So we can conclude that "These variables are jointly significant."


Rejection Rule


F-distribution is always positive in value as evident by the fact that SSR can only increase if variables are dropped. Because of this, there is no two tail test like t-test. Rather this one form of F-testing works for general multiple linear hypotheses.

Why do we need this test?

As you can see from our example, three variables that were insignificant in individual t-test turned out to be significant in joint f-testing. This sugguests that these three variables have multicolinearity. A good way to get rid of the structural multicolinearity would be actually doing more research and getting more data so you can come up with one composite variable that will replace all three variables. In the mean time, we use F-test as the bandage to run the regression while someone else fixes the problem with dataset.

MA and AR Models
Examples of Nonstationary Time Series
Condition for AR(1) to be stationary
So what does it mean for a time series to be stationary? That is if a time series' stochastic properties and its temporal dependence structure do not change over time. Functionally, there are Three conditions.

The expected value is not a function of time. So the mean will be constant regardless of time. Graphically, the best fit line will have slope of 0.

The variance is not a function of time. So the variance will be constant regardless of time. Graphically, the height of local minimum to local maximum should be constant.
The Covariance between any two point in time must be consistent. Graphically, the distance between one local mimimum to the next local minimum must be the constant.

To satisfy this, let's look at the equation for AR(1) model.
X(t) = {a \times X(t-1) +c} + u \times e(t)
We will extract the roots of the polynomial. If all roots are outside the unit circle, the process is stationary.
